{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-47-56-029Z","slug":"one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams","locale":"de","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:48:11.434Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/de/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/de/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-47-56-029Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5e23bd6661ed61df952a39bf65d61ca0a0d01f23e047cdf168f7bbdac407baeb","outputHash":"dc939ff088e1e35580bf79c7735011256f35e6b1b75aca8ea6fe6c7597c39b75","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that feature teams should begin new services with the simplest possible persistence—typically a key‑value (KV) store such as Redis, DynamoDB, or S3—rather than defaulting to relational or document databases. It explains how to “think in keys,” showing that most data can be modeled as hierarchical keys (e.g., `user/123/friends`) and that KV patterns can even represent graphs or trees without the overhead of a full‑blown graph or SQL engine. The piece lists clear criteria for when KV stores are advantageous (massive scale, primary‑key access, simple or hierarchical data) and when they are unsuitable (property searches, joins, complex constraints). The tone is a practical tutorial with occasional rhetorical “trick” framing, using the metaphor of “starting with a simple key‑value lock and only upgrading the lock when you need more security.” The intended audience is software engineers and technical leads who design data layers for new features or micro‑services.","totalInputTokens":8799,"totalOutputTokens":2488,"totalCacheReadTokens":2304,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":13156,"totalCostUsd":0.00079100099